 control than those who enter into such relations can imagine. Through unusually close ethnographic work in West African migrant communities in Amsterdam, Apostolos Andrikopoulos reveals the unseen dynamics of kinship through shared papers, the tensions of race and gender that develop in mutually beneficial marriages, and the vast, informal networks of people, information, and documentation on which migrants rely. Throughout Argonauts of West Africa, Andrikopoulos demonstrates how inequality, exclusionary practices, and the changing policies of an often-violent state demand innovative ways of doing kinship to successfully navigate complex migration routes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfricansxKinshipzNetherlandszAmsterdam. 0aAfricansxLegal status, laws, etc.zNetherlandszAmsterdam. 0aAfricanszNetherlandszAmsterdamxSocial conditions. 0aAfricans-Migrations. 0aIllegal immigrationzNetherlands. 0aNoncitizenszNetherlandszAmsterdamxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aunauthorized migration, kinship, identity documents, social navigation, citizenship, immigration policies, marriage, visa, Europe, West Africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822617/original  a978